      "doc": null,
      "titulo": "Avaliação da Robustez e Segurança de Sistemas Críticos Baseados em Linux através de Injeção de Falhas",
      "titulo_en": "Assessment of Security-Relevant Robustness of Linux-Based Critical Systems via Fault Injection",
      "enquadramento": "Linux is widely used as a software platform in embedded, cyber-physical, vehicular, industrial, edge, and other systems that may execute critical tasks. In these settings, kernel-level failures are not merely dependability concerns: crashes, hangs, severe timing delays, communication disruption, memory corruption, and loss of logging can compromise availability, timely availability, operational integrity, and accountability. These properties are security-relevant because they support trusted system operation and, in cyber-physical contexts, may also affect safety.\r\n\r\nSoftware-implemented fault injection provides a controlled way to study how low-level implementation faults propagate into observable system failures. Existing work in the group already uses a Linux kernel fault injector derived from SWIFI, capable of injecting binary-level fault operators such as branch deletion, pointer corruption, omitted initialization, allocation failures, buffer-copy perturbations, off-by-one changes, and kernel text bit flips. Previous experiments focused mainly on CPU, memory, and I/O stress workloads and on general robustness outcomes.\r\n\r\nThis thesis will revisit that experimental setup from a cybersecurity perspective. Instead of treating robustness failures as generic failures, the work will analyze them as security-relevant degradation modes for Linux-based critical systems. The thesis will first replicate the existing setup and experiments, then extend the evaluation with workloads that represent critical services such as periodic computation, network communication, filesystem logging, process lifecycle management, and mixed cyber-physical execution scenarios. The resulting failure profiles will be analyzed in terms of availability loss, timely-availability violations, operational integrity deviations, detection or containment by kernel mechanisms, and silent failures.\r\n\r\nA final part of the work will investigate how the observed results depend on the Linux kernel version. The student will test the injector on a newer kernel within the same injector family, compare the failure profile with the previous version, and evaluate the technical viability and expected effort of porting the injector to a more recent Linux kernel version, such as Linux 5.4.\r\n",
      "objetivos": "This thesis has the following main objectives:\r\n•  Replicate the existing Linux kernel fault-injection setup and baseline experiments, including the original CPU, memory, and I/O stress workloads.\r\n•  Systematize the available injected fault types according to their potential security relevance, especially faults that may affect availability, timely execution, operational integrity, memory safety, or containment.\r\n•  Extend the workload set with representative services of Linux-based critical systems, including periodic/timeliness workloads, network communication, filesystem logging, process/service lifecycle, memory activity, and mixed workloads.\r\n•  Define and implement a failure-classification methodology that distinguishes injection success, activation evidence where available, workload-visible degradation, crashes, hangs, timing violations, kernel warnings, detector reports, and silent failures.\r\n•  Analyze how different fault types and workloads influence the observed failure profile and identify which combinations produce security-relevant robustness failures.\r\n•  Compare the failure profile across the original Linux kernel version and a newer kernel version supported by the current injector, when feasible.\r\n•  Evaluate the technical viability, risks, and required changes for porting the injector to a recent Linux kernel version, such as Linux 5.4.\r\n",
      "plano1": "[--/09/2026 to 11/10/2026] Literature Review and Problem Framing\r\nStudy software fault injection, Linux kernel fault-injection techniques, robustness testing, availability-oriented security, and the security relevance of failures in Linux-based embedded and cyber-physical systems. Refine the thesis framing around security-relevant robustness failures rather than exploit generation or direct access-control bypass.\r\n[12/10/2026 to 08/11/2026] Replication of Existing Setup\r\nInstall and document the current Linux kernel fault-injection environment, reproduce the original injector configuration, and replicate the existing CPU, memory, and I/O stress experiments. Establish a baseline failure taxonomy and logging procedure.\r\n[09/11/2026 to 06/12/2026] Workload and Measurement Design\r\nSelect and prototype additional workloads, including periodic/timeliness execution, network communication, filesystem logging, process lifecycle, memory activity, and a mixed critical-system scenario. Define metrics for availability, timely availability, operational integrity, and detection/containment.\r\n[07/12/2026 to --/01/2027] Thesis Proposal Writing\r\nConsolidate the problem statement, methodology, baseline replication results, workload plan, expected evaluation metrics, risk analysis, and final thesis proposal.\r\n",
      "plano2": "[--/02/2027 to 28/02/2027] Experiment Harness and Logging Infrastructure\r\nImplement or refine scripts to automate experiment execution, workload launch, fault injection, kernel log collection, workload metric collection, timeout handling, reboot/recovery procedures, and result classification.\r\n[01/03/2027 to 26/03/2027] Extended Workload Campaign on Baseline Kernel\r\nRun fault-injection campaigns using the expanded workload set on the replicated baseline kernel. Collect evidence of crashes, hangs, timing degradation, service disruption, corrupted or missing outputs, kernel warnings, oopses, watchdog events, and other observable effects.\r\n[27/03/2027 to 16/04/2027] New Kernel Experiment and Failure-Profile Comparison\r\nTest the existing injector on a newer compatible Linux kernel version, when feasible. Repeat a selected subset of campaigns and compare the resulting failure profile with the baseline version, focusing on differences in manifestation, detection, containment, and workload sensitivity.\r\n[17/04/2027 to 07/05/2027] Viability Assessment for Porting to Linux 5.4\r\nAnalyze the technical obstacles for porting the injector to a recent Linux kernel such as 5.4, including changes in kernel layout, symbol handling, instruction patterns, module/core targeting, protection mechanisms, and experiment automation. Produce a reasoned assessment of feasibility, effort, and risk.\r\n[08/05/2027 to --/06/2027] Result Analysis and Thesis Writing\r\nAnalyze results across fault types, workloads, and kernel versions. Discuss the security relevance of observed failures for Linux-based critical systems, limitations of the approach, and future work. Compile the dissertation and prepare the final presentation.\r\n",
