      "doc": null,
      "titulo": "Manutenção Preditiva e Diagnóstico em Tempo Real de Regimes Operacionais Isolados para Frotas de Transporte Público",
      "titulo_en": "Predictive Maintenance and Real-Time Isolate Operational Regimes Diagnostics for Public Transport Fleets",
      "enquadramento": "Modern public transport systems, particularly bus fleets, are under constant pressure to maximize operational efficiency, minimize downtime, and reduce maintenance costs. Machine Learning (ML) and Artificial Intelligence (AI) have emerged as pivotal tools in enabling Predictive Maintenance (PdM).\r\n\r\nThis thesis is integrated into the FCT-funded project FOX. The core mission of FOX is to transition fleet management from reactive or scheduled maintenance to an intelligent, data-driven proactive strategy. In urban bus fleets, anticipating a breakdown is not just about fixing a part—it is a critical logistical requirement. Early detection allows operators to safely reroute a failing bus back to the maintenance depot before a catastrophic on-road breakdown occurs, avoiding traffic disruptions and ensuring passenger safety.\r\n\r\nDeveloping a robust PdM system for public transport introduces three interconnected challenges that standard ML models struggle to solve simultaneously:\r\n\r\nThe Lead-Time Prediction Problem: Models must not only detect that a anomaly is occurring but predict it with enough advance notice to logistically return the bus to the depot.\r\n\r\nThe \"False Positive\" Regime Problem: Mechanical components often exhibit varied \"working regimes\" (e.g., due to extreme weather, heavy passenger loads, or specific routes). These shifts mimic anomalies but are entirely benign. Models must distinguish between actual faults and alternative normal operational regimes.\r\n\r\nThe Black-Box Problem: When a failure occurs or is imminent, fleet managers and mechanics cannot rely on a silent binary alert. They require real-time, interpretable explanations to understand why the system flagged a fault, allowing them to prep the right spare parts immediately.\r\n",
      "objetivos": "The main objective of this thesis is to develop an end-to-end data processing and machine learning framework for the FOX project that addresses one of these three pillars. Specifically, the project will:\r\n\r\nIdentify Isolate Operational Regimes: Design unsupervised or semi-supervised clustering/classification algorithms to identify and catalog non-failure operational regimes, minimizing false maintenance alarms.\r\n",
      "plano1": "1. Literature Review and Problem Definition\r\n•\tReview predictive maintenance and anomaly detection techniques. \r\n•\tStudy operational regime identification methods in industrial systems. \r\n•\tAnalyze existing unsupervised and semi-supervised clustering algorithms. \r\n•\tDefine research gaps and thesis objectives.\r\n\r\n2. Data Collection and Preprocessing\r\n•\tGather historical operational and sensor data. \r\n•\tIdentify relevant process variables and operational parameters. \r\n•\tClean noisy and incomplete data. \r\n•\tPerform normalization, synchronization, and feature engineering. \r\n•\tConduct exploratory data analysis (EDA).\r\n\r\n3. Unsupervised Operational Regime Discovery\r\n•\tImplement clustering algorithms such as: \r\no\tK-Means \r\no\tDBSCAN \r\no\tGaussian Mixture Models (GMM) \r\no\tHierarchical Clustering \r\n•\tIdentify patterns corresponding to normal/non-failure operational regimes. \r\n•\tDetermine optimal number of clusters and regime boundaries. \r\n•\tVisualize regime separations and temporal behaviors.\r\n\r\n4. Baseline Evaluation\r\n•\tDefine evaluation metrics: \r\no\tFalse alarm rate \r\no\tSilhouette score \r\no\tCluster stability \r\no\tPrecision and recall \r\n•\tCompare clustering methods. \r\n•\tEstablish baseline maintenance alarm performance.\r\n",
      "plano2": "1. Semi-Supervised Model Development\r\n•\tIncorporate limited labeled maintenance/failure data. \r\n•\tDevelop semi-supervised approaches such as: \r\no\tLabel propagation \r\no\tConstrained clustering \r\no\tSelf-training methods \r\n•\tImprove discrimination between operational regimes and anomalies.\r\n2. Optimization and Robustness Analysis\r\n•\tOptimize hyperparameters and model architecture. \r\n•\tEvaluate robustness under: \r\no\tNoise \r\no\tMissing data \r\no\tSensor drift \r\no\tChanging operational conditions \r\n•\tMinimize false maintenance alarms while preserving detection sensitivity.\r\n3. Validation and Prototype Development\r\n•\tValidate models using unseen operational datasets. \r\n•\tCompare results against baseline maintenance systems. \r\n•\tDevelop a prototype for real-time regime identification and monitoring. \r\n•\tImplement alarm decision logic based on operational regimes.\r\n",
