      "titulo": "Um modelo fundacional para detecção e previsão de crises epilépticas  - ForEpi",
      "titulo_en": "A foundation model for epilepsy seizure detection and forecasting - ForEpi",
      "enquadramento": "Epilepsy affects approximately 46 million people worldwide, and up to one-third are drug-resistant, continuing to have seizures despite optimal medical treatment. Effective epilepsy management depends critically on accurate seizure documentation and forecasting, yet this remains one of the field's most persistent unsolved problems. Patient self-reported diaries, the current standard of care, have an average accuracy below 50%, leading to treatment decisions based on unreliable data.\r\nA problem with seizure detection and prediction is the fact that seizures are very rare events, and consequently, a very low number of seizures per patient. This fact limits the capacity to develop proper personalized seizures detectors/forecasters. A solution to improve training is to adopt a transfer learning strategy or more recently, to consider foundation models. It is believed that self-supervised foundation models (FMs), trained to represent the refractory epilepsy domain by learning patterns from long-term multimodal data, represent an important step forward. Existing FMs for brain data are not focused on epilepsy and do not integrate multimodal data collected across both hospital and real-life settings.\r\n",
      "objetivos": "The main goal of this master thesis is to develop signal processing and AI algorithms for the development of large-scale foundation models that can be fine-tuned for patient-specific seizure detection and forecasting. These models will be trained on the EPILEPSIAE database (comprising over 45,000 hours of annotated scalp and invasive EEG from more than 250 patients) as well as legacy sqEEG data from our international collaborators, which will be used to strengthen the pre-training corpus. Synthetic data generation will further support model training and privacy-preserving data sharing. Building on these foundation models, personalised seizure detectors/forecasters will be developed through patient-specific fine-tuning. Models will be developed on a 10GPU cluster, with 700GB RAM and 13TB of storage for this task.",
      "plano1": "(1) literature review, which will not only reinforce the definition of the objectives and novelty of the proposed work, but also gain advanced knowledge regarding foundation models development;  (2 months)\r\n\r\n(2) Development of preliminary models; (1 month)\r\n\r\n\r\n(3) Intermediate report writing (1 month)\r\n",
      "plano2": "(1) Development of foundation models. Different methodological approaches will be faced, for example, developing models for invasive/non-invasive patients. (3 months)\r\n\r\n(2) Development of personalised detectors/forecasters; (2 months)\r\n\r\n(3)Thesis writing (2 Months)\r\n",
