      "doc": null,
      "titulo": "Avaliação da estabilidade de modelos combinados dinamicamente para previsão de séries temporais",
      "titulo_en": "Evaluating the Stability of Dynamic Ensembles for Time Series Forecasting",
      "enquadramento": "In recent years, forecasting models based on deep neural networks have emerged as a powerful alternative to traditional local approaches like ARIMA. While their accuracy and efficiency have been widely studied, less attention has been paid to the stability of their forecasts over time.\r\n\r\nIn many operational contexts, forecasts are produced regularly and serve as the foundation for critical business decisions, from inventory planning to resource allocation. In such settings, forecast stability becomes a key requirement: not only should forecasts be accurate, but they should also remain reasonably consistent over time. Forecast instability can lead to frequent and expensive adjustments in supply chain plans, diminish trust in the forecasting system, and complicate decision-making processes.\r\n\r\nForecast stability can be categorized into two primary forms [1]: vertical stability, which concerns the consistency of forecasts for the same target date across different forecast origins, and horizontal stability, which addresses the smoothness of forecasts across the forecast horizon from a single origin. Vertical stability helps avoid costly forecast revisions that disrupt planning cycles, while horizontal stability prevents erratic behavior across time steps that could lead to inefficient operations and amplification of demand fluctuations, such as the bullwhip effect in supply chains [1].\r\n\r\nDynamic ensembles, which adaptively combine multiple forecasting models over time, are increasingly used to improve predictive accuracy. However, their stability properties remain underexplored. This thesis addresses this gap by systematically evaluating the stability of dynamic ensemble methods for time series forecasting. \r\n\r\n\r\nKeywords: Time series forecasting, deep learning, ensemble learning, dynamic ensembles, forecast stability, empirical study",
      "objetivos": "This is a fundamental research project aimed at advancing our understanding of forecast stability in dynamic ensemble methods. The work is methodological in nature, focusing on empirical analysis rather than application development.\r\n\r\nResearch Goals:\r\n• Conduct a comprehensive empirical study comparing dynamic ensembles for time series forecasting in terms of stability\r\n• Evaluate forecasting methods based on vertical stability, horizontal stability, and predictive accuracy\r\n• Identify which dynamic ensemble configurations (e.g., weighting schemes, update frequency, base models) yield stable yet accurate forecasts\r\n• Provide practical guidelines for practitioners on choosing ensemble strategies when forecast stability is critical\r\n\r\nLearning Outcomes:\r\n• Develop scientific research and communication skills\r\n• Consolidate knowledge of ensemble methods and time series forecasting\r\n• Strengthen skills in forecast evaluation beyond accuracy metrics\r\n• Gain experience in systematic empirical experimentation and statistical analysis\r\n\r\nExpected Contributions:\r\n• A comprehensive empirical comparison of dynamic ensemble methods regarding forecast stability\r\n• Quantitative analysis of vertical and horizontal stability across multiple datasets and ensemble configurations\r\n• Practical recommendations for balancing accuracy and stability in operational forecasting\r\n• Open-source code repository with experimental framework\r\n",
      "plano1": "• Literature review on dynamic ensembles, forecast stability, and time series forecasting evaluation\r\n• Identification of key libraries and frameworks (e.g., statsforecast, neuralforecast, metaforecast)\r\n• Formulation of research questions and hypotheses\r\n• Design of experimental methodology, including stability metrics and statistical tests\r\n• Initial implementation of experimental framework",
      "plano2": "• Collect and preprocess time series datasets (e.g., HuggingFace Hub)\r\n• Implement base forecasting models based on deep learning\r\n• Implement dynamic ensemble methods with varying weighting schemes\r\n• Execute experiments and evaluate methods based on vertical stability, horizontal stability, and forecast accuracy\r\n• Statistical analysis and result compilation",
      "sugestao_juri": null,
      "tem_juri": false,
      "add_aluno_pos_inicio_candidatura": false,
      "inicio_candidaturas": false,
      "condicoes": "Prerequisites:\r\n• Proficiency in Python programming\r\n• Familiarity with machine learning workflows\r\n• Basic knowledge of statistics and probability\r\n• Understanding of supervised learning and classification\r\n• Basic knowledge of time series forecasting is a plus\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n• Access to computational resources for running experiments",
      "observacoes": "References:\r\n\r\n1. Godahewa, R., Bergmeir, C., Baz, Z. E., Zhu, C., Song, Z., García, S., & Benavides, D. (2025).\r\nOn forecast stability. International Journal of Forecasting.",
