      "id": "cmplj03e804lofza92ojgqtfl",
      "codigo_proposta": 146,
      "periodo_submissao": false,
      "doc": null,
      "titulo": "Avaliação de arrependimento de validação cruzada em problemas de classificação",
      "titulo_en": "Evaluating Cross-validation Regret in Classification Problems",
      "enquadramento": "Cross-validation (CV) is the predominant approach for performance estimation and model selection in machine learning. By evaluating models on held-out data, CV yields more reliable estimates than in-sample (based on the training data) metrics, enabling the selection of algorithms that generalize well to unseen data.\r\n\r\nA key design choice in CV is how to partition the data into training and validation sets. Various solutions exist in the literature, including holdout, bootstrapping, and k-fold CV. These techniques are often repeated for more robust results, or stratified to preserve class distributions. Several empirical studies have compared different CV techniques regarding their ability to estimate performance—that is, how close the performance estimates obtained from CV are to the true performance of a given model [1, 2]. However, an overlooked aspect of CV evaluation concerns model selection: how often does the CV procedure select the best attainable model (selection accuracy), and what is the performance gap when it does not (selection regret)?\r\n\r\nThis thesis addresses this gap by systematically evaluating CV techniques from a model selection perspective, focusing on selection accuracy and regret rather than performance estimation alone. We also focus on supervised classification problems, where the goal is to predict a categorical label based on a set of features.",
      "objetivos": "This is a fundamental research project aimed at advancing our understanding of CV techniques for model selection in classification problems. The work is methodological in nature, focusing on empirical analysis rather than application development.\r\n\r\nResearch Goals:\r\n• Conduct a comprehensive empirical study comparing CV techniques for model selection in classification\r\n• Evaluate CV approaches based on selection accuracy (how often the best model is chosen) and selection regret (the performance gap when it is not)\r\n• Identify which CV configurations (e.g., number of folds, repetitions, stratification) yield the most reliable model selection\r\n• Provide practical guidelines for practitioners on choosing CV strategies for classification tasks\r\n\r\nLearning Outcomes:\r\n• Develop scientific research and communication skills\r\n• Consolidate knowledge of CV techniques and their theoretical foundations\r\n• Develop skills in supervised classification and algorithm evaluation\r\n• Gain experience in systematic empirical experimentation and statistical analysis\r\n\r\nExpected Contributions:\r\n• A comprehensive empirical comparison of CV techniques for model selection in classification\r\n• Quantitative analysis of selection accuracy and regret across multiple datasets and classifiers\r\n• Practical recommendations for CV configuration in classification tasks\r\n• Open-source code repository with experimental framework",
      "plano1": "• Literature review on CV methods, model selection, supervised classification, and related empirical studies\r\n• Identification of key libraries and frameworks (e.g., scikit-learn, OpenML)\r\n• Formulation of research questions and hypotheses\r\n• Design of experimental methodology, including evaluation metrics and statistical tests\r\n• Initial implementation of experimental framework",
      "plano2": "• Collect and preprocess datasets (e.g., OpenML CC18 benchmark suite)\r\n• Implement a diverse set of classifiers (e.g., gradient boosted trees, random forest, neural networks,\r\nlogistic regression, SVM)\r\n• Implement and configure CV techniques: K-fold CV, repeated K-fold, stratified K-fold, holdout,\r\nand bootstrapping\r\n• Execute experiments and evaluate CV performance based on selection accuracy, selection regret,\r\nestimation bias, and downstream predictive performance\r\n• Statistical analysis and result compilation\r\n• Thesis writing and revision",
      "sugestao_juri": null,
      "tem_juri": false,
      "add_aluno_pos_inicio_candidatura": false,
      "inicio_candidaturas": false,
      "condicoes": "Prerequisites:\r\n• Proficiency in Python programming\r\n• Familiarity with scikit-learn and machine learning workflows\r\n• Basic knowledge of statistics and probability\r\n• Understanding of supervised learning and classification\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n• Access to computational resources for running experiments",
      "observacoes": "References:\r\n\r\n1. Cerqueira, V., Torgo, L., & Mozetič, I. (2020). Evaluating time series forecasting models: An\r\nempirical study on performance estimation methods. Machine Learning, 109(11), 1997–2028.\r\n2. Cerqueira, V., Torgo, L., & Soares, C. (2023). Model selection for time series forecasting: An\r\nempirical analysis of multiple estimators. Neural Processing Letters, 55(7), 10073–10091.\r\n\r\nOther resources:\r\n\r\n- https://scikit-learn.org/stable/api/sklearn.model_selection.html#splitters",
